      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can the ombudsman help if my parent refuses to let them get involved?",
          "answer": "No — ombudsmen cannot act on behalf of a resident who refuses their involvement. The resident must consent to ombudsman services, though family members can still receive information about rights and options. If your parent has cognitive impairment and you have legal authority, discuss this with the ombudsman directly."
        },
        {
          "question": "What's the difference between calling the ombudsman versus reporting abuse to the state?",
          "answer": "Ombudsmen handle quality of care complaints and advocacy, while suspected abuse or neglect must be reported to the NC Division of Health Service Regulation or local law enforcement. For serious safety concerns like physical abuse, financial exploitation, or medical neglect, call both — the ombudsman can advocate while regulators investigate. You can file abuse reports at (800) 624-3004."
        },
        {
          "question": "Will the facility know I complained if I call the ombudsman?",
          "answer": "Services are confidential unless you specifically request that your identity be shared. Ombudsmen can investigate concerns and work with facilities without revealing who made the complaint. However, if formal mediation or specific advocacy is needed, some level of disclosure may be necessary to resolve the issue effectively."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can the ombudsman help us choose a facility before admission?",
          "answer": "Yes — ombudsmen provide education about resident rights, facility selection guidance, and can explain what to look for in admission agreements. They cannot approve or disapprove specific facilities, but can help you understand inspection reports, resident rights, and warning signs. They cannot help with Medicaid applications or funding — contact your local Department of Social Services for financial assistance."
        }
      ],
