      "faqs": [
        {
          "question": "Can my parent keep their house if it's worth more than $2,000?",
          "answer": "Yes, the home is exempt from asset limits if your parent intends to return home, equity is under $730,000, or if a spouse, child under 21, or disabled child lives there. The home only counts toward the $2,000 limit if none of these conditions apply."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens to my parent's Social Security and pension income?",
          "answer": "Your parent pays almost all income toward their care cost, keeping only $70/month for personal needs. They can also deduct health insurance premiums and certain spousal allowances before calculating what goes to the facility."
        },
        {
          "question": "How long is the waitlist for home care services really?",
          "answer": "HCBS waivers like CAP/DA can have waitlists of several months to multiple years depending on your region and your parent's priority level. Nursing home Medicaid typically has no waitlist, though finding an available bed may take time."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can I apply on behalf of my elderly parent?",
          "answer": "Yes, you can apply as an authorized representative if your parent cannot apply themselves due to physical or mental limitations. You'll need to complete additional forms establishing your authority to act on their behalf."
        },
        {
          "question": "What if my parent gave money to grandchildren in the past few years?",
          "answer": "Gifts or asset transfers within 5 years of applying create penalty periods that delay Medicaid coverage. The penalty equals the gift amount divided by the average monthly nursing home cost in your area, creating months of ineligibility."
        },
        {
          "question": "Can my parent apply for this and regular Medicaid at the same time?",
          "answer": "Your parent typically needs ABD Medicaid (for those 65+, blind, or disabled) first, then adds long-term care coverage. You can apply for both simultaneously through the same application process."
        },
        {
          "question": "What happens if my parent's condition improves after enrollment?",
          "answer": "Medicaid conducts periodic reviews to ensure your parent still meets the Nursing Facility Level of Care requirement. If their condition significantly improves, they may lose long-term care coverage but could retain basic Medicaid."
        },
        {
          "question": "Does this cover assisted living or just nursing homes?",
          "answer": "It covers nursing home care directly, plus assisted living and home care through HCBS waivers. However, assisted living and home care options often have waitlists and may not be available immediately in all areas."
        }
      ],
